{
  "question": "Which best describes the Gumbel-Softmax distribution?",
  "options": {
    "A": "It is a method for interpolating between discrete distributions.",
    "B": "It uses the argmax operation to select elements from a probability distribution.",
    "C": "It involves computing the maximum value of a logarithmic probability.",
    "D": "It provides a way to sample from a discrete distribution without differentiation."
  },
  "answer": "B",
  "explanation": "The Gumbel-Softmax distribution is defined as \(Z = \text{onehot}\left(\arg\max_i \left(G_i + \log(p_i)\right)\right)\), where \(G_i\) represents the Gumbel noise term and \(p_i\) are the probabilities of each element in the distribution. The key point here is that it uses the argmax operation to select elements from a probability distribution, which aligns with option B."
}

